"Scripture Narrative | VOD Slide Build Out\nSession\nNumber Session Topics Completed? Time\n1 Set Up + Structure of Scripture Yes\n2 Creation + Fall Yes\n3 Covenants + Law Yes\n4 Covenant Consequences, Part 1 Yes\n5 Covenant Consequences, Part 2 Yes\n6 Covenant Worship Yes\nUnited and Divided Kingdom,\n7 Part 1 Yes\nUnited and Divided Kingdom,\n8 Part 2 Yes\n9 Major + Minor Prophets Yes\n10 A Return + a New Covenant Yes\n11 Gospels Part 1 Yes\n12 Gospels Part 2 Yes\n13 Acts Yes\n14 Pauline Epistles Yes\n15 Hebrews Yes\n16 Revelation Yes\n17 The Whole Story Yes\nVOD Videos\n1\n2\nSession 1: Set Up + Structure of the Story\nTeacher: Mark Yarbrough\nTitle Slide: Set Up + Structure of the Story || Creation + Fall || Covenants + Law ||\nCovenant Consequences + Law, Part 1 || Covenant Consequences + Law, Part 2 ||\nCovenant Worship || United and Divided Kingdom, Part 1 || United and Divided\nKingdom, Part 2 || Major + Minor Prophets || A Return + a New Covenant || Gospels,\nPart 1 || Gospels, Part 2 || Acts || Pauline Epistles || Hebrews || Revelation || The Whole\nStory (0:10)\nSlide 1: (0:38)\nThis is one continuous story: starting in Genesis and ending to Revelation.\nSlide 2: (0:51)\nScripture Narrative is going to frame for you the greatest story ever told.\nSlide 3: (1:36)\n5 - 12 - 5 - 5 - 12\n4 - 1 - 21 - 1\nSlide 4: he Structure of Our English Bibles - Old Testament (3:20)\nThe Old Testament has 39 books.\nThe New Testament has 27 books.\nSlide 5: The Structure of Our English Bibles (3:42)\nGenesis - Exodus - Leviticus - Numbers - Deuteronomy\nThe first 5 books that we have are referenced as the Torah.\nThe Torah means “law.”\nSlide 6: The Structure of Our English Bibles - Old Testament (5:23)\nThe second number, 12, references books of theological history.\n3\nJoshua, Judges, Ruth, 1 & 2 Samuel, 1 & 2 Kings\n1 & 2 Chronicles, Esther, Ezra, Nehemiah\nSlide 7: The Structure of Our English Bibles - Old Testament (6:31)\nThe third number is 5 and it references the five books of poetry, or wisdom literature.\nJob, Psalms, Proverbs, Ecclesiastes, Song of Solomon\nSlide 8: The Structure of Our English Bibles - Old Testament (7:55)\nThe next two numbers - 5 and 12 - reference the major and minor prophets.\nSlide 9: The Structure of Our English Bibles - Old Testament (8:40)\nThe only difference between the major and minor prophets is their size, or length.\nSlide 10: The Structure of Our English Bibles - Old Testament (9:07)\nThe Prophetic Books:\nMajor: Isaiah, Jeremiah, Ezekiel, Daniel, Lamentations\nMinor: Hosea, Joel, Amos, Obadiah, Jonah, Micah, Nahum, Habakkuk, Zephaniah,\nHaggai, Zechariah, Malachi\nSlide 11: A Summary of the Old Testament Categories (9:15)\n5 - Torah or Law\n12 - Theological History\n5 - Poetry\n5 - Major Prophets\n12 - Minor Prophets\nSlide 12: A Summary of the Old Testament Categories (9:41)\nWe can “put our arms” around the 5 books of poetry and the 17 books of the prophets\nand pick them all up, placing them, chronologically, within the 12 books of history.\nSlide 13: The Structure of Our English Bibles - New Testament (11:05)\n4\nThe New Testament Categories\n4 - 1 - 21 - 1\nSlide 14: The Structure of Our English Bibles - New Testament (11:43)\nThe first number, 4, refers to the four Gospel accounts.\nMatthew, Mark, Luke, and John\nSlide 15: The Gospels (12:23)\nJesus is the fulfillment of all of the Old Testament promises.\nSlide 16: The Structure of Our English Bibles - New Testament (13:48)\nThe second number, 1, refers to the one book of theological history.\nThe Book of Acts\nSlide 17: The Structure of Our English Bibles - New Testament (14:22)\nActs is almost like Part 2 of the Gospel message. Luke, who wrote the gospel of Luke,\nalso wrote Acts.\nActs carries the gospel forward, showing us the growth and expansion.\nSlide 18: The Structure of Our English Bibles - New Testament (15:16)\nThe third number, 21, refers to the letters written to people and churches in the 1st\nCentury.\nMany of these letters are birthed within the book of Acts.\nSlide 19: The Structure of Our English Bibles - New Testament (16:41)\nThe last number, 1, refers to the one book of prophecy or apocalyptic writing.\nThis is the book of Revelation.\n5\nSlide 20: The Structure of Our English Bibles - New Testament (16:57)\nRevelation tells us in an impactful way what God is going to do in the future.\nGod’s plan that started in the garden of Eden is completed in Revelation.\nSlide 21: A Summary of New Testament Categories (18:40)\n4 - Gospels\n1 - Acts, book of History\n21 - Letters\n1 - Revelation, Prophecy\nSlide 22: (19:05)\nIt is the greatest story ever told. It is Scripture’s Narrative.\n6\nSession 2: Creation + Fall\nTeacher: Mark Yarbrough\nTitle Slide: Set Up + Structure of the Story || Creation + Fall || Covenants + Law ||\nCovenant Consequences + Law, Part 1 || Covenant Consequences + Law, Part 2 ||\nCovenant Worship || United and Divided Kingdom, Part 1 || United and Divided\nKingdom, Part 2 || Major + Minor Prophets || A Return + a New Covenant || Gospels,\nPart 1 || Gospels, Part 2 || Acts || Pauline Epistles || Hebrews || Revelation || The Whole\nStory (0:10)\nSlide 1: In The Beginning… (00:29)\nWe’re going to talk about 3 C’s:\n1. Creation (Genesis 1)\n2. Caretakers (Genesis 2-3)\n3. The Continuation of the Story (Genesis 4-11)\nSlide 2: In The Beginning… (01:20)\nThe thesis of the bible can be seen as: “In the beginning, God created the heavens and\nthe earth.”\nSlide 3:In The Beginning… (01:53)\nThe first six days are paired in two groups:\n● Days 1-3: Deal with structure and formation.\n● Days 4-6: Deal with filling that structure.\nSlide 4: In The Beginning… (02:35)\nIn this account, there is a refrain that show up over and over:\nGod creates, he speaks… and it was good.\nSlide 5: The ‘Very Good’ creation (05:14)\nGenesis 1:31\n“God saw all that he had made, and it was very good. And there was evening, and there\nwas morning—the sixth day.”\n7\nSlide 6: The ‘Very Good’ creation (05:50)\nGod is creator, what God creates is good, and humanity, created by God, makes\ncreation very good.\nSlide 7: The Image of God (06:15)\nThe pinnacle of the created order is male and female, created in the image of God.\nThat phrase, the image of God, is also known as the imago dei.\nSlide 8: The Command to the Caretakers (09:18)\nGenesis 2:16-17\n“And the Lord God commanded the man, “You are free to eat from any tree in the\ngarden; 17 but you must not eat from the tree of the knowledge of good and evil, for\nwhen you eat from it you will certainly die.”\nSlide 9: The Tension for the Caretakers (10:07)\nGenesis 2:18\n“18 The Lord God said, “It is not good for the man to be alone. I will make a helper\nsuitable for him.”\nSlide 10: The Caretakers (11:15)\nIt’s a beautiful picture:\n1. Man is created.\n2. Man is not meant to be alone.\n3. Out of man, God creates woman as an equal, a unit, a team.\n4. They are asked to steward God’s creation (Genesis 1:26-28).\nSlide 11: The Garden of Eden from Genesis 2 (12:00)\nThis Garden is a picture of perfection and peace.\nThis it the garden of shalom.\n8\nSlide 12: The Crisis in Genesis 3 (13:00)\nGenesis 3:1\n“Now the serpent was more crafty than any of the wild animals the Lord God had made.\nHe said to the woman, “Did God really say, ‘You must not eat from any tree in the\ngarden’?”\nSlide 13: The Crisis in Genesis 3 (15:25)\nAdam and Eve hide from God, and God asks: “Where are you?”\nAdam blames Eve and Eve blames the serpent.\nSlide 14: The Problem and Hope from Genesis 3 (18:12)\nWe have a problem and that problem is called sin. We cannot provide a solution. Our\nonly hope is that God is able to do something about it.\nSlide 15: (no title) (18:31)\nThe continuation of the story in Genesis 4-11\nSlide 16: The Continuation of the Story… (19:25)\nWhen they leave the garden, they have kids and Cain kills Abel.\nRight after sin, they have families, and death enters the story through the first murder.\nSlide 17: The Continuation of the Story… (20:17)\nGenesis chapter 5 is a long geneology to show us how death affects us all.\nSlide 18: The Continuation of the Story… (20:44)\nGenesis 6-9 tells the story of Noah. It comes about because now all of humanity is\nsinful.\nSin rejects who God is and what he wants.\n9\nSlide 19: The Continuation of the Story… (21:30)\nGenesis 10 shows us what is called “the table of nations” as a way to indicate that\nthough the world is now re-populated after the flood, sin is still prevalent.\nSlide 20: The Continuation of the Story… (21:40)\nIn Genesis 11, we see the “Tower of Babel.” Humanity builds this tower to the heavens\nto make their name great… not God’s name.\nSlide 21: The Continuation of the Story… (23:00)\nIn humanity’s worst moment, God was already at work:\n● Genesis 3 -\n○ God made skins to cover Adam and Eve’s shame\n○ He pushed humanity out of the Garden in grace.\n○ He punished the serpent for his role in the fall.\n● Genesis 5 - God saved Enoch from death.\n● Genesis 6-9 - God protected Noah and his family\nSlide 22: Equal in Attributes (24:07)\nThe First Gospel Promise\nGenesis 3:15\n“And I will put enmity between you and the woman, and between your offspring and\nhers; he will crush your head, and you will strike his heel.”\n10\nSession 3: Covenants + Law\nTeacher: Mark Yarbrough\nTitle Slide: Set Up + Structure of the Story || Creation + Fall || Covenants + Law ||\nCovenant Consequences + Law, Part 1 || Covenant Consequences + Law, Part 2 ||\nCovenant Worship || United and Divided Kingdom, Part 1 || United and Divided\nKingdom, Part 2 || Major + Minor Prophets || A Return + a New Covenant || Gospels,\nPart 1 || Gospels, Part 2 || Acts || Pauline Epistles || Hebrews || Revelation || The Whole\nStory (0:10)\nSlide 1: There is a Solution (00:25)\nThere is a solution to our problem, and it is found in the fact that God has revealed\nhimself as a covenant God.\nSlide 2: The Covenants (0:52)\n1. The Abrahamic Covenant – a covenant given to Abraham\n2. The Mosaiac Covenant – a covenant given to Moses\nSlide 3: What is a Covenant? (01:45)\nCovenant: a legal term denoting a formal and legally binding declaration; a declaration\nof benefits to be given by one party to another with or without conditions.\nSlide 4: What is a Covenant? (04:47)\nSometimes we will reference these covenants as one of two types:\n1. Unconditional: no strings attached\n2. Conditional: strings attached, like a contract.\nSlide 5: The First Big Covenant: The Abrahamic Covenant (05:50)\nGenesis 12:1-3\n“The Lord had said to Abram, “Go from your country, your people and your father’s\nhousehold to the land I will show you. “I will make you into a great nation, and I will\nbless you; I will make your name great, and you will be a blessing. I will bless those who\nbless you, and whoever curses you I will curse; and all peoples on earth will be blessed\nthrough you.”\n11\nSlide 6: The Storyline Slows Down (6:35)\nIn Genesis 12, God shows up, selects, and speaks to a man named Abram.\nSlide 7: The Abrahamic Covenant (8:00)\nHow do we know if a covenant is unconditional or conditional?\nAlways look at the pronouns.\nGenesis 12 - “I (God) will…”\nSlide 8: The Abrahamic Covenant (9:27)\nThe only way this promise is going to work is if God is good at his word.\nSlide 9: The Abrahamic Covenant (9:35)\nThere are 3 things that God promises in this covenant:\n1. God will lead Abraham and give him a land.\nSlide 10: The Abrahamic Covenant (10:05)\nThere are 3 things that God promises in this covenant:\n1. God will lead Abraham and give him a land.\n2. God will make Abraham the father of a very significant nation.\nSlide 11: The Abrahamic Covenant (10:37)\nThere are 3 things that God promises in this covenant:\n1. God will lead Abraham and give him a land.\n2. God will make Abraham the father of a very significant nation.\n3. God will bless all peoples on earth through Abraham.\nSlide 12: The Rest of Genesis (11:50)\nFrom Genesis 12 to Genesis 50, this promise is re-iterated from Abraham, to his son,\nIsaac, to his son, Jacob, and to his twelve sons, one of whom was Joseph.\n12\nBy the time we get to the end of the book of Genesis, the line of Abraham is in Egypt.\nSlide 13: The Book of Exodus (14:03)\nThere is a radical change of circumstance to start the book of Exodus: God’s people are\ngrowing but the Egyptian Pharoah starts to oppress the people of Israel.\nSlide 14: The Book of Exodus (15:26)\nAs readers of the text and followers of the story, we are now asking: How is God going\nto keep his promise alive?\nSlide 15: The Second Big Covenant: The Mosaic Covenant (15:44)\nThis covenant is made with and through Moses to the people of Israel.\nIt is an conditional covenant.\nSlide 16: The Second Big Covenant: The Mosaic Covenant (16:45)\nIn the story, the people are now out of Egypt, in the wilderness, and God gives them the\nLaw.\nThey are going to the Land of Promise from the Abrahamic Covenant, but they need a\nlaw and a structure.\nSlide 17: The Book of Exodus (17:15)\n“The Book of Exodus is all about the nation of Israel receiving the 10 commandments\nand the entire legal system around these commandments.\nSlide 18: The Laws of Exodus (17:30)\nIt’s not just 10 commandments, though. There are 613 laws that are mentioned in the\nPentateuch.\nThese laws help the people of Israel know how to live in right relationship with God.\nSlide 19: The Direction of the Laws (18:05)\n13\n“Vertical” Laws - There are very specific laws about worship with God.\n“Horizontal” Laws - How the people of Israel are meant to deal with one another.\nSlide 20: The Mosaic Covenant (18:26)\nWhen you take all of these laws and pull them together, you get what we call the\n“Mosaic Covenant.” It is like a contract that God makes with his people and there are\nconsequences for their obedience or lack thereof.\nSlide 21: The Book of Leviticus (19:31)\nThe book of Leviticus records all of the laws for the priests. In particular, it gives us\ndetails about “the sacrificial system.”\nSlide 22: The Four Main Points of the Sacrificial System (20:18)\nThe sacrificial system is meant to show us that:\n1. a holy God cannot tolerate sin,\nSlide 23: The Four Main Points of the Sacrificial System (20:44)\nThe sacrificial system is meant to show us that:\n1. a holy God cannot tolerate sin,\n2. God stipulates that the penalty for sin is death,\nSlide 24: The Four Main Points of the Sacrificial System (21:44)\nThe sacrificial system is meant to show us that:\n1. a holy God cannot tolerate sin,\n2. God stipulates that the penalty for sin is death,\n3. God will accept a temporary substitute for the sin of a sinner,\nSlide 25: The Four Main Points of the Sacrificial System (22:15)\nThe sacrificial system is meant to show us that:\n1. a holy God cannot tolerate sin,\n2. God stipulates that the penalty for sin is death,\n3. God will accept a temporary substitute for the sin of a sinner,\n4. God’s grace allows that substitution to occur, and for the final judgment to be\npostponed until sin is dealt with in totality.\n14\nSlide 26: The Book of Numbers (23:15)\nThe book of Numbers is about numbers. It is about two censuses that are taken of the\npeople of Israel.\nSlide 27: Census #1 in Numbers (23:46)\nThe first census in Numbers is when the people of God are first ready to go into the\nLand of Promise. They are meant to count their people before they enter.\nSlide 28: Census #2 in Numbers (25:14)\nThe second census in Numbers is when the people of God are again ready to go into\nthe Land of Promise after 40 years of wilderness wandering.\nThis census is to count the new generation who will be charged with entering the Land.\nSlide 29: The Book of Deuteronomy (25:25)\nThe book of Deuteronomy is about the second “law” or the presentation of the law to the\nnew generation that is going to go into the Land.\nIt is a re-iteration of the Law, not a new law.\nSlide 30: Deuteronomy 28 (26:24)\nDeuteronomy 28:1-2\n“If you fully obey the Lord your God and carefully follow all his commands I give you\ntoday, the Lord your God will set you high above all the nations on earth. 2 All these\nblessings will come on you and accompany you if you obey the Lord your God…”\nSlide 31: The Blessings of Obedience (27:18)\nIf the people of God obey the Mosaic Covenant, they will be blessed with:\n● Crops\n● Kids\nSlide 32: The Curses of Disobedience (27:42)\nDeuteronomy 28:15\n15\n“However, if you do not obey the Lord your God and do not carefully follow all his\ncommands and decrees I am giving you today, all these curses will come on you and\novertake you…”\nSlide 33: As the Torah Ends… (28:30)\nAs the story ends, the reader is meant to be asking: how are these two covenants going\nto work together? How will God’s unconditional covenant with Abraham fit with his\nconditional covenant with Moses?\n16\nSession 4: Covenant Consequences, Part 1\nTeacher: Brittany West\nTitle Slide: Set Up + Structure of the Story || Creation + Fall || Covenants + Law ||\nCovenant Consequences + Law, Part 1 || Covenant Consequences + Law, Part 2 ||\nCovenant Worship || United and Divided Kingdom, Part 1 || United and Divided\nKingdom, Part 2 || Major + Minor Prophets || A Return + a New Covenant || Gospels,\nPart 1 || Gospels, Part 2 || Acts || Pauline Epistles || Hebrews || Revelation || The Whole\nStory (0:10)\nSlide 1: Deuteronomy 28 (0:30)\nThe Mosaic Covenant is a “conditional covenant and the consequences for obedience\nor disobedience are laid out in Deueteronomy 28.\nSlide 2: Remembering our Mnemonic Device (0:55)\n5 - 12 - 5 - 5 - 12\n5 - Torah or Law\n12 - Theological History\n5 - Poetry\n5 - Major Prophets\n12 - Minor Prophets\nSlide 3: The 12 Books of History (1:26)\nWhat should be noted about the historical books is that they are more than letters,\npieces of advice, or examples to follow. These books are recording what actually\nhappened to the people of God during this timeframe.\nSlide 4: Covenant Consequences (1:47)\nThis teaching will cover: Joshua, Judges, Ruth, and 1 & 2 Samuel.\nSlide 5: The Book of Joshua (2:00)\nThe main theme of the book of Joshua is: Land and Conquest.\n17\nSlide 6: The Introduction of Joshua (2:14)\nJoshua 1:1-6\nAfter the death of Moses the servant of the Lord, the Lord said to Joshua son of Nun,\nMoses’ aide: 2 “Moses my servant is dead. Now then, you and all these people, get\nready to cross the Jordan River into the land I am about to give to them—to the\nIsraelites. 3 I will give you every place where you set your foot, as I promised Moses.”\nSlide 7: The Introduction of Joshua (2:37)\nJoshua 1:1-6, cont.\n“Your territory will extend from the desert to Lebanon, and from the great river, the\nEuphrates—all the Hittite country—to the Mediterranean Sea in the west. 5 No one will\nbe able to stand against you all the days of your life. As I was with Moses, so I will be\nwith you; I will never leave you nor forsake you. 6 Be strong and courageous, because\nyou will lead these people to inherit the land I swore to their ancestors to give them.”\nSlide 8: The Charge to Joshua (3:05)\nThe main summary point of what God is saying here is: get ready, we’re going to\noccupy the land and take hold of the promises that I spoke to your forefathers.\nSlide 9: The book of Joshua (3:40)\nJoshua 2: Rahab hides the Israelite Spies\nSlide 10: The book of Joshua (4:18)\nJoshua 2: Rahab hides the Israelite Spies\nJoshua 3: The Israelites cross the Jordan River\nSlide 11: The book of Joshua (4:50)\nJoshua 2: Rahab hides the Israelite Spies\nJoshua 3: The Israelites cross the Jordan River\nJoshua 5: Circumcision and Passover at Gilgal\nSlide 12: The book of Joshua (5:22)\n18\nJoshua 2: Rahab hides the Israelite Spies\nJoshua 3: The Israelites cross the Jordan River\nJoshua 5: Circumcision and Passover at Gilgal\nJoshua 6: The fall of Jericho\nSlide 13: The book of Joshua (6:38)\nJoshua 2: Rahab hides the Israelite Spies\nJoshua 3: The Israelites cross the Jordan River\nJoshua 5: Circumcision and Passover at Gilgal\nJoshua 6: The fall of Jericho\nJoshua 7: Achan’s Sin of Coveteousness\nSlide 14: The First Covenant Renewal in Joshua (7:35)\nJoshua 8 - an interchange between the Abrahamic Covenant (unconditional) and the\nMosaic Covenant (conditional).\nIsrael sinned, there are consequences, but God is still faithful to his unconditional\npromises.\nSlide 15: The Second Covenant Renewal in Joshua (8:35)\nJoshua 24 - This renewal ceremony consists of Joshua charging the Israelites to follow\nGod only.\nSlide 16: The Book of Judges (9:35)\nThe main theme is the book of Judges: the rebellion of the people and the rescue of\nGod.\nSlide 17: The Central Issue with the book of Judges (11:22)\nJudges 2:10\n“After that whole generation had been gathered to their ancestors, another generation\ngrew up who knew neither the Lord nor what he had done for Israel.”\n19\nSlide 18: The Cycle of Sin in Judges (11:50)\nS - Sin\nO - Oppression\nR - Repentance for unfaithfulness to Mosaic Covenant\nD - Deliverance\nSlide 19: The Judges (12:23)\n● Judges 3 - Ehud\n● Judges 4 - Deborah and Barak\nSlide 20: The Judges (12:40)\n● Judges 3 - Ehud\n● Judges 4 - Deborah and Barak\nSlide 21: The Judges (12:52)\n● Judges 3 - Ehud\n● Judges 4 - Deborah and Barak\n● Judges 6-8 - Gideon\nSlide 22: The Judges (13:10)\n● Judges 3 - Ehud\n● Judges 4 - Deborah and Barak\n● Judges 6-8 - Gideon\n● Judges 11 - Jephthah\nSlide 23: The Judges (13:56)\n● Judges 3 - Ehud\n● Judges 4 - Deborah and Barak\n● Judges 6-8 - Gideon\n● Judges 11 - Jephthah\n● Judges 13-16 - Samson\n20\nSlide 24: The Overall Message of Judges (14:00)\nJudges 21:25\n“In those days Israel had no king; everyone did as they saw fit.”\nGod was still faithful through it all.\n21\nSession 5: Covenant Consequences, Part 2\nTeacher: Brittany West\nTitle Slide: Set Up + Structure of the Story || Creation + Fall || Covenants + Law ||\nCovenant Consequences + Law, Part 1 || Covenant Consequences + Law, Part 2 ||\nCovenant Worship || United and Divided Kingdom, Part 1 || United and Divided\nKingdom, Part 2 || Major + Minor Prophets || A Return + a New Covenant || Gospels,\nPart 1 || Gospels, Part 2 || Acts || Pauline Epistles || Hebrews || Revelation || The Whole\nStory (0:10)\nSlide 1: The Book of Ruth (00:10)\nThe book of Ruth intros the idea that a demonstration of faithfulness works with the\nsovereignty of God’s plan.\nSlide 2: Two Dominant Connections of Ruth (00:20)\n1. Ruth 1:1 - “In the days when the judges ruled, there was a famine in the land.”\n2. Ruth 4:17 - “The women living there said, “Naomi has a son!” And they named\nhim Obed. He was the father of Jesse, the father of David.”\nSlide 3: The Main Thought of Ruth (1:40)\nGod is faithful and God has a plan.\nSlide 4: Ruth’s Declaration (1:45)\nRuth 1:16-17\n“But Ruth replied, “Don’t urge me to leave you or to turn back from you. Where you go I\nwill go, and where you stay I will stay. Your people will be my people and your God my\nGod. 17 Where you die I will die, and there I will be buried. May the Lord deal with me,\nbe it ever so severely, if even death separates you and me.”\nSlide 5: The United Kingdom: 1 and 2 Samuel (2:42)\n1 Samuel - The Kingdom of Israel begins and God appoints a king.\n2 Samuel - God promises an eternal king.\nSlide 6: The Main Theme of 1 Samuel (3:02)\n22\nIsrael puts their trust in a king, and not in God.\nSlide 7: 1 Samuel 4-7 (3:22)\nIn these chapters, often known as the Ark Narratives, the people of God are putting their\ntrust in the things of God rather than in God himself.\nSlide 8: 1 Samuel 8 (4:09)\nThe Israelites desire and heartbeat was for their human king and not for God as their\nking.\nSlide 9: An Overview of the Rest of Samuel (4:16)\n● 1 Samuel 9 - The people elect Saul\n● 1 Samuel 15 - The Lord Reject Sauls\n● 1 Samuel 16 - David anointed as the second king of Israel; he is a man after\nGod’s own heart.\n● 1 Samuel 17 - David and Goliath\n● 1 Samuel 18-31 - Conflict between Saul and David\nSlide 10: The Main Theme of 2 Samuel (5:23)\nThe main theme of 2 Samuel is the Davidic covenant, which is the ideological summit of\nthe Old Testament.\nSlide 11: The Covenants of God (5:35)\nThe Davidic covenant is God’s response to our failing in the Mosaic covenant in light of\nhis Abrahamic covenant.\nIt is the hinge point between the Old Testament and the introduction to the promised\nking to come: Jesus.\nSlide 12: The Davidic Covenant - 2 Samuel 7 (5:51)\n● V2 - David in palace while Ark of the Covenant is in temporary dwelling.\nSlide 13: The Davidic Covenant - 2 Samuel 7 (6:07)\n23\n● V2 - David in palace while Ark of the Covenant is in temporary dwelling.\n● V5 - David wants to build God a temple\nSlide 14: The Davidic Covenant - 2 Samuel 7 (6:10)\n● V2 - David in palace while Ark of the Covenant is in temporary dwelling.\n● V5 - David wants to build God a temple\n● V6 - God tells David he doesnt need anything from him.\nSlide 15: The Davidic Covenant - 2 Samuel 7 (6:17)\n● V2 - David in palace while Ark of the Covenant is in temporary dwelling.\n● V5 - David wants to build God a temple\n● V6 - God tells David he doesnt need anything from him.\n● V8 - “Now therefore,” – God turns the conversation from Earthly to Eternal.\nSlide 16: The Davidic Covenant - 2 Samuel 7 (6:26)\n● V2 - David in palace while Ark of the Covenant is in temporary dwelling.\n● V5 - David wants to build God a temple\n● V6 - God tells David he doesnt need anything from him.\n● V8 - “Now therefore,” – God turns the conversation from Earthly to Eternal.\n● V9-10 - Connection with covenant language (Genesis 12)\nSlide 17: The Davidic Covenant - 2 Samuel 7 (6:36)\n● V11 - God will build a house for David\n● V13 - The earthly promise that David’s son would build God a temple.\n● V14 - The language of adoption is used in reference to God.\nSlide 18: The Davidic Covenant - 2 Samuel 7 (7:06)\n2 Samuel 7:16\n“Your house and your kingdom will endure forever before me; your throne will be\nestablished forever.’”\nSlide 19: The Davidic Covenant - 2 Samuel 7 (7:29)\nThe Davidic Covenant Promises:\n1. V11 - the temple; a physical building\n24\n2. V12 - the seed; a forever physical reigning Messiah.\n3. V16 - the kingdom; an eternal kingdom that will last forever\nSlide 20: The Davidic Covenant - 2 Samuel 7 (8:22)\nDavid’s Response in 2 Samuel 7:18-29\n“Then King David went in and sat before the Lord, and he said:\n“Who am I, Sovereign Lord, and what is my family, that you have brought me this far?\n19 And as if this were not enough in your sight, Sovereign Lord, you have also spoken\nabout the future of the house of your servant—and this decree, Sovereign Lord, is for a\nmere human!”\n25\nSession 6: Covenant Worship\nTeacher: Brittany West\nTitle Slide: Set Up + Structure of the Story || Creation + Fall || Covenants + Law ||\nCovenant Consequences + Law, Part 1 || Covenant Consequences + Law, Part 2 ||\nCovenant Worship || United and Divided Kingdom, Part 1 || United and Divided\nKingdom, Part 2 || Major + Minor Prophets || A Return + a New Covenant || Gospels,\nPart 1 || Gospels, Part 2 || Acts || Pauline Epistles || Hebrews || Revelation || The Whole\nStory (0:10)\nSlide 1: The 5 Books of Poetry (00:29)\n5 - 12 - 5 - 5 - 12\nSlide 2: The Books of Covenant Worship (00:45)\nPsalms, Proverbs, Ecclesiastes, Song of Solomon, and the book of Job\nSlide 3: The 5 Books of Poetry (1:14)\nThese 5 books of poetry are full of wisdom and worship and they give practical\nguidance to those under the Mosaic Covenant.\nSlide 4: The Psalms (1:23)\nThe intent is to foster an intimate relationship with the Lord, which we learn from\nexample.\nSlide 5: The Psalms (1:36)\nThe Book of Psalms is actually comprised of 5 sub-books:\n● Book 1 - Psalms 1-41\n● Book 2 - Psalm 42-72\n● Book 3 - Psalm 73-89\n● Book 4 - Psalm 90-106\n● Book 5 - Psalm 107-150\nSlide 6: 2 Main Types of Psalms (2:10)\n26\nThe two main forms, or types, of Psalms are:\n● Psalms of lament\n● Psalms of praise\nSlide 7: Psalms of Lament (2:15)\nPsalms of lament are expressing anguish to God for either:\n● Trouble caused by God\n● External circumstances\n● Personal weaknesses\nSlide 8: The Structure of a Psalm of Lament (2:42)\n1. The Lament - the words of anguish\n2. The reason for the lament - the poetic illustration of sorrow\n3. Confession of trust - turning of author’s gaze off circumstances\n4. Petition - the request of saving or for release from the circumstances\n5. Vow of praise - the declaration of God’s nature and character to refocus from\nwhat has been ailing the Psalmist.\nSlide 9: Psalms of Praise (3:40)\nA song rendering to God with excited delight because of his:\n● Faithful character\n● Powerful works and acts.\nSlide 10: Psalms of Praise (3:52)\nThe core themes found in a Psalm of Praise are:\n1. The displays of creation\n2. The universality of God’s presence and eternal reign\n3. God’s work in Israel’s history to keep them from forgetting.\nSlide 11: The Book of Proverbs (4:17)\nProverbs teaches us how to live practically and carry out the Mosaic Law in day-to-day\nlife.\nSlide 12: The Book of Proverbs (4:24)\n27\nThe main characters in the Proverbs are:\n● The wise\n● The foolish\n● The sluggard, the mocker, the simple, the forbidden woman.\nSlide 13: Ecclesiastes (5:08)\nEcclesiastes describes a search for the meaning of life which is only found in God.\nSlide 14: Song of Solomon (5:16)\nSong of Solomon provides practical wisdom about marriage, love, and sexuality, while\noffering a biblical picture of God’s love for us.\nSlide 15: The book of Job (5:26)\nThe book of Job gives a personal testimony of how life is complex but our creator God\nis sovereign.\nSlide 16: The Two Main Truths of Wisdom Literature (5:38)\n1. Truth about God\na. He is creator.\nb. He is to be feared and worshipped.\nc. He is a covenant keeper.\nSlide 17: The Two Main Truths of Wisdom Literature (5:55)\n2. Truth about Man\na. We are fallen and full of sin.\nb. Wisdom for us comes from a fear and worship of the Lord.\nc. We are covenant betrayers in need of saving.\n28\nSession 7: United and Divided Kingdom, Part 1\nTeacher: Jake Daghe\nTitle Slide: Set Up + Structure of the Story || Creation + Fall || Covenants + Law ||\nCovenant Consequences + Law, Part 1 || Covenant Consequences + Law, Part 2 ||\nCovenant Worship || United and Divided Kingdom, Part 1 || United and Divided\nKingdom, Part 2 || Major + Minor Prophets || A Return + a New Covenant || Gospels,\nPart 1 || Gospels, Part 2 || Acts || Pauline Epistles || Hebrews || Revelation || The Whole\nStory (0:10)\nSlide 1: The 12 Books of History (00:45)\n5 - 12 - 5 - 5 - 12\nWe are jumping back into the 12 books of history by studying:\n1 and 2 Kings and 1 and 2 Chronicles\nSlide 2: The United Kingdom (2:05)\nThe kings of the United Kingdom:\n● Saul - 1 Samuel 8\n● David - 1 Samuel 16\n● Solomon - 1 Kings 1\nSlide 3: The United Kingdom (4:25)\nThe kings of the United Kingdom:\n● Saul - 1 Samuel 8\n● David - 1 Samuel 16\nSlide 4: The United Kingdom (5:40)\nThe kings of the United Kingdom:\n● Saul - 1 Samuel 8\n● David - 1 Samuel 16\n● Solomon - 1 Kings 1\nSlide 5: The Breaking Point of the Kingdom (6:45)\nDeuteronomy 17:16-17\n29\n“The king, moreover, must not acquire great numbers of horses for himself or make the\npeople return to Egypt to get more of them, for the Lord has told you, “You are not to go\nback that way again.” 17 He must not take many wives, or his heart will be led astray.\nHe must not accumulate large amounts of silver and gold.”\nSlide 6: Solomon’s Disobedience (8:02)\nSolomon accumulated great wealth.\n1 Kings 10:14\n“The weight of the gold that Solomon received yearly was 666 talents,”\nSlide 7: Solomon’s Disobedience (8:20)\nSolomon accumulated chariots and horsemen from Egypt.\n1 Kings 10:26, 28\n“Solomon accumulated chariots and horses; he had fourteen hundred chariots and\ntwelve thousand horses, which he kept in the chariot cities and also with him in\nJerusalem…. Solomon’s horses were imported from Egypt and from Kue.”\nSlide 8: Solomon’s Disobedience (8:33)\nSolomon accumulated many wives.\n1 Kings 11:1-3\n“King Solomon, however, loved many foreign women besides Pharaoh’s\ndaughter—Moabites, Ammonites, Edomites, Sidonians and Hittites. 2 They were from\nnations about which the Lord had told the Israelites, “You must not intermarry with them,\nbecause they will surely turn your hearts after their gods.” Nevertheless, Solomon held\nfast to them in love. 3 He had seven hundred wives of royal birth and three hundred\nconcubines, and his wives led him astray.”\nSlide 9: Key Statements (9:07)\n1 Kings: When leadership goes wrong.\n2 Kings: Disobedience of the leaders leads to the defeat of the people.\n30\nSlide 10: Key Statements (9:34)\n1 Chronicles: History of God’s people from Adam to Solomon.\n2 Chronicles: History of God’s people from Solomon to the fall of Jerusalem.\n31\nSession 8: United and Divided Kingdom, Part 2\nTeacher: Jake Daghe\nTitle Slide: Set Up + Structure of the Story || Creation + Fall || Covenants + Law ||\nCovenant Consequences + Law, Part 1 || Covenant Consequences + Law, Part 2 ||\nCovenant Worship || United and Divided Kingdom, Part 1 || United and Divided\nKingdom, Part 2 || Major + Minor Prophets || A Return + a New Covenant || Gospels,\nPart 1 || Gospels, Part 2 || Acts || Pauline Epistles || Hebrews || Revelation || The Whole\nStory (0:10)\nSlide 1: The Tale of Two Kingdoms (00:30)\nThe United Kingdom of Israel gets divided into two kingdoms:\n1. Northern Kingdom of Israel\n2. Southern Kingdom of Judah\nSlide 2: The Northern Kingdom (1:28)\nMade up of 10 tribes.\nThe capital was Samaria.\nSlide 3: Map of Northern Kingdom (1:35)\nTO FILL IN HERE\nSlide 4: The Southern Kingdom (1:43)\nMade up of 2 tribes - Judah and Benjamin.\nThe capital was Jerusalem.\nSlide 5: The Fall of the Northern Kingdom (2:17)\nThe Northern Kingdom of Israel was conquered by the Assyrians in 722 BC.\nSlide 6: The Fall Southern Kingdom (4:18)\nThe Southern Kingdom of Judah was conquered by the Babylonians in 586 BC.\nSlide 7: What Can We Learn from These Books? (5:41)\n32\n1. Sin is utterly devastating.\nSlide 8: What Can We Learn from These Books? (6:14)\n1. Sin is utterly devastating.\n2. God is incredibly merciful and patient.\nSlide 9: What Can We Learn from These Books? (7:11)\n1. Sin is utterly devastating.\n2. God is incredibly merciful and patient.\n3. The people around us really do influence us.\nSlide 10: What Can We Learn from These Books? (9:13)\n1. Sin is utterly devastating.\n2. God is incredibly merciful and patient.\n3. The people around us really do influence us.\n4. God is actively arranging the course of human affairs.\nSlide 11: God’s Faithfulness even in the Consequences (10:55)\n1 Kings 11:12-13\n“Nevertheless, for the sake of David your father, I will not do it during your lifetime. I will\ntear it out of the hand of your son. 13 Yet I will not tear the whole kingdom from him, but\nwill give him one tribe for the sake of David my servant and for the sake of Jerusalem,\nwhich I have chosen.””\n33\nSession 9: Major + Minor Prophets\nTeacher: Jake Daghe\nTitle Slide: Set Up + Structure of the Story || Creation + Fall || Covenants + Law ||\nCovenant Consequences + Law, Part 1 || Covenant Consequences + Law, Part 2 ||\nCovenant Worship || United and Divided Kingdom, Part 1 || United and Divided\nKingdom, Part 2 || Major + Minor Prophets || A Return + a New Covenant || Gospels,\nPart 1 || Gospels, Part 2 || Acts || Pauline Epistles || Hebrews || Revelation || The Whole\nStory (0:10)\nSlide 1: The Divided Kingdom (00:31)\nThe Kingdom of Israel splits into two kingdoms:\n1. The Northern Kingdom of Israel\n2. The Southern Kingdom of Judah\nSlide 2: The Structure of the Scripture (1:08)\n5 - 12 - 5 - 5 - 12\n5 Major Prophets\n12 Minor Prophets\nSlide 3: The Major and Minor Prophets (1:23)\nThe two numbers - 5 and 12 - reference the major and minor prophets.\nThe only difference between the major and minor prophets is their size, or length.\nSlide 4: Consequence and Hope (2:30)\nThe prophetic books, while they are trying to urge a warning, are full of hope.\nSlide 5: The Framework of the Time of the Prophets (4:03)\n1. Pre-exile\n2. Mid-Exile\n3. Post-Exile\nSlide 6: The New Covenant (5:00)\n34\nThe New Covenant is introduced by the prophets and is the fourth major covenant in\nScripture.\nSlide 7: The Posture of the Prophets (7:20)\nThe prophets aren’t rude or angry, but they are trying to call out the danger of sin and\nGod’s coming judgment.\nSlide 8: Pre-Exile Books (8:47)\nThough the timing of some of the prophetic books is debated, we would say that there\nare 11 pre-exile books.\nSlide 9: Obadiah (9:05)\nObadiah was written to the other nations surrounding Israel to talk about the Day of the\nLord that is coming.\nSlide 10: Joel (10:25)\nJoel wrote to the Southern Kingdom of Judah to surrender their lives to God.\nSlide 11: Amos (11:02)\nAmos wrote to the Northern Kingdom of Israel, encouraging them to follow God by\ntaking care of the least, the last, and the lost.\nSlide 12: Hosea (11:35)\nHosea wrote to the Northern Kingdom, showing the people a representation of God’s\nfaithfulness to his covenant.\nSlide 13: Micah (12:22)\nMicah wrote to the Southern Kingdom of Judah, encouraging them to lean into the\nmercy and care of those who needed it most.\nSlide 14: Isaiah (12:38)\n35\nIsaiah was largely written to the Southern Kingdom, and has many examples of future\nprophecy fulfilled by Jesus.\nSlide 15: Nahum (13:05)\nNahum wrote to the other nations surrounding Israel to remind the people that the Lord\nis a strong tower that the righteous can run to.\nSlide 16: Zephaniah (13:16)\nZephaniah wrote to the Southern Kingdom to remind them that judgment is coming, but\nthat God is still interested in rejoicing over his people.\nSlide 17: Jonah (13:43)\nJonah wrote to the other nations surrounding Israel to show the power, mercy, and\ngrace of God.\nSlide 18: Habakkuk (13:51)\nHabakkuk wrote to the Southern Kingdom to remind them that the righteous will live by\nfaith.\nSlide 19: Jeremiah (14:10)\nJeremiah was written to the Southern Kingdom and references the New Covenant for\nGod’s people.\nSlide 20: Pre-exile Prophets (14:29)\nTake note that the majority of the prophets are pre-exile, which tells us something about\nthe character and nature of God. He is slow to anger and abounding in steadfast love.\nSlide 21: Mid-Exile Prophets (15:02)\n● Ezekiel - God can bring life back into our dry bones.\n● Lamentations - God’s mercies are new every day.\n● Daniel - God is with Daniel even in captivity.\nSlide 22: Post-Exile Prophets (16:00)\n36\n● Haggai\n● Zechariah\n● Malachi\n37\nSession 10: A Return + A New Covenant\nTeacher: Josh Crawford\nTitle Slide: Set Up + Structure of the Story || Creation + Fall || Covenants + Law ||\nCovenant Consequences + Law, Part 1 || Covenant Consequences + Law, Part 2 ||\nCovenant Worship || United and Divided Kingdom, Part 1 || United and Divided\nKingdom, Part 2 || Major + Minor Prophets || A Return + a New Covenant || Gospels,\nPart 1 || Gospels, Part 2 || Acts || Pauline Epistles || Hebrews || Revelation || The Whole\nStory (0:10)\nSlide 1: 3 Final Old Testament Books (00:45)\n● Esther\n● Ezra\n● Nehemiah\nSlide 2: The Book of Esther (0:55)\nEsther makes a bold request before the king of Persia, and the people of God are\nspared through the work of Esther\nSlide 3: The summary of Esther (2:40)\nEven if God is seemingly absent, he is always faithfully at work.\nSlide 4: The Book of Ezra (2:47)\nThis book takes place after the exile.\nEzra is a priest and a scribe and asks the King if he can return to Jerusalem to rebuild\nthe temple.\nSlide 5: The Book of Ezra (3:24)\nThe book ends with a strange sense of despair because the people are back in the\nland, but the presence of God is not in the temple.\nSlide 6: The Book of Nehemiah (3:45)\nAbout a man, Nehemiah, who requests to go back to rebuild the wall around Jerusalem.\n38\nSlide 7: The Book of Nehemiah (4:30)\nThe book of Nehemiah also ends with a strange note of despair: the wall is re-built but\nthere is still something missing in their worship of God.\nSlide 8: The Core Realization of the Old Testament (4:50)\nBeyond the practices and religious exercises lies an issue of the heart: there is\nsomething deeper going on in the story.\nWe need a savior to be our solution.\nSlide 9: Clinging to the Promises of God (6:05)\nJeremiah 31:31-32\n““Behold, the days are coming, declares the Lord, when I will make a new covenant with\nthe house of Israel and the house of Judah, 32 not like the covenant that I made with\ntheir fathers on the day when I took them by the hand to bring them out of the land of\nEgypt, my covenant that they broke, though I was their husband, declares the Lord.”\nSlide 10: Clinging to the Promises of God (6:24)\nJeremiah 31:33-34\n“33 For this is the covenant that I will make with the house of Israel after those days,\ndeclares the Lord: I will put my law within them, and I will write it on their hearts. And I\nwill be their God, and they shall be my people. 34 And no longer shall each one teach\nhis neighbor and each his brother, saying, ‘Know the Lord,’ for they shall all know me,\nfrom the least of them to the greatest, declares the Lord. For I will forgive their iniquity,\nand I will remember their sin no more.”\nSlide 11: The Four Promises of the New Covenant (6:52)\nGod, communicating to the Jewish people, says:\n1. I will be their God\n2. They will be my people\n3. I will live among them\n4. I will forgive their sin.\nSlide 12: 430 Years of Silence (8:20)\n39\nThe intertestamental period is 430 years of waiting, of silence, of no new prophecy.\n40\nSession 11: Gospels, Part 1\nTeacher: Grant Partrick\nTitle Slide: Set Up + Structure of the Story || Creation + Fall || Covenants + Law ||\nCovenant Consequences + Law, Part 1 || Covenant Consequences + Law, Part 2 ||\nCovenant Worship || United and Divided Kingdom, Part 1 || United and Divided\nKingdom, Part 2 || Major + Minor Prophets || A Return + a New Covenant || Gospels,\nPart 1 || Gospels, Part 2 || Acts || Pauline Epistles || Hebrews || Revelation || The Whole\nStory (0:10)\nSlide 1: Jesus in the Scripture (00:44)\nJesus exists on every page of Scripture, and he is the point of the story that God is\nrevealing.\nSlide 2: The New Testament Structure (2:21)\n4 - 1 - 21 - 1\nThe four represents for the four gospels: Matthew, Mark, Luke, and John.\nSlide 3: The Culmination (3:16)\nThrough Jesus birth, ministry, teaching, death, resurrection, and ascension, recorded in\nthese four books, we encounter the word of God made flesh.\nSlide 4: The Intertestamental Period (3:34)\nThe gap between where the Old Testament ends and the New Testament begins.\nSlide 5: The Intertestamental Period (4:10)\n● One common language - Greek - via Alexander the Great\nSlide 6: The Intertestamental Period (4:49)\n● One common language - Greek - via Alexander the Great\n● One consistent road system via Rome and Pax Romana\n41\nSlide 7: The Intertestamental Period (5:23)\nThe people of God were still eagerly waiting for the fulfillment of the prophecies and\ncovenants.\nSlide 8: “Messianic” Hope (6:06)\n“Messianic” in Hebrew or “Christ” in Greek means “the anointed one”\nSlide 9: Prophecies that Jesus Fulfilled Perfectly (6:47)\n● Isaiah 7:14 - Born of a virgin\n● Micah 5:2 - Born in Bethlehem\n● Hosea 11:1 - Called out of Egypt\n● Zechariah 9:9 - Enter Jerusalem riding a donkey\n● Deuteronomy 18:15 - A prophet like Moses\n● Isaiah 40:3 - Called a Nazarene\n● Isaiah 35:5-6 - Heal the blind, deaf, and lame\nSlide 10: Prophecies that Jesus Fulfilled Perfectly (8:06)\n“For Jesus to have fulfilled just 8 of these prophecies, the odds of that happening are 1\nin 100 quadrillion.”\nSlide 11: Jesus on the Road to Emmaus (11:18)\nLuke 24:27\n“And beginning with Moses and all the Prophets, he explained to them what was said in\nall the Scriptures concerning himself.”\nSlide 12: Types of Christ (12:00)\nJesus is the better:\n● Adam\n● Isaac\n● Joseph\n● Moses\n● Passover Lamb\n42\nSlide 13: Types of Christ (13:06)\nJesus is the better:\n● Bronze Serpent\n● Boaz\n● Job\n● David\n● Esther\nSlide 14: Types of Christ (13:59)\nJesus is the better:\n● Jonah\n● Temple\n● Prophet\n● Priest\n● King\n● Sacrifice\n● Feast\n43\nSession 12: Gospels, Part 2\nTeacher: Grant Partrick\nTitle Slide: Set Up + Structure of the Story || Creation + Fall || Covenants + Law ||\nCovenant Consequences + Law, Part 1 || Covenant Consequences + Law, Part 2 ||\nCovenant Worship || United and Divided Kingdom, Part 1 || United and Divided\nKingdom, Part 2 || Major + Minor Prophets || A Return + a New Covenant || Gospels,\nPart 1 || Gospels, Part 2 || Acts || Pauline Epistles || Hebrews || Revelation || The Whole\nStory (0:10)\nSlide 1: Synoptic Gospels (02:23)\nMatthew, Mark, and Luke, are referenced as the synoptic gospels because they are\ncoming from a similar view: from the Earth up.\nSlide 2: The Gospel of John (2:40)\nJohn is telling the gospel strory from Heaven down, introducing Jesus in John 1 as the\n“Word of God.”\nSlide 3: The Distinction of Audiences (2:58)\n● Matthew: written to Jews\n● Mark: written to Romans\n● Luke: written to Gentiles\n● John: written to everyone\nSlide 4: Comparing the Gospels (4:11)\n| | Matthew | Mark | Luke | John |\n| Author | Disciple of Jesus, Tax collector | John Mark, writing for Peter | Gentle physician, traveled with Paul | Disciple of Jesus, loved by Jesus |\n| Date | 75–80 AD | 65–70 AD | 60–85 AD | 80–90 AD |\n| Key Themes | Kingdom of God, Jewish law | Action over teaching, Powerful Savior | God's plan, Savior for Gentiles | Jesus’ deity, eternal life |\n| Christ | Messiah & King | Suffering Servant | Son of Man | Son of God |\nSlide 5: The Life of Jesus (4:30)\nHis life, in some ways, can be divided into three waves:\n1. Obscurity\n2. Popularity\n3. Rejection\nSlide 6: Jesus’ Birth (5:00)\n● Jesus was from the line of Abraham and David\n● Conceived of the Holy Spirit\n● Born of the virgin Mary\n● Born in Bethlehem\n● Honored as King by shepherds\n● Receives gifts from Magi\nSlide 7: Orthodox Theology about Jesus (5:58)\nHe is 100% God and 100% man. Two natures in one Person.\nSlide 8: Jesus’ Disciples (6:05)\nJesus called 12 men to “come and follow him.” To become “fishers of men.”\nSlide 9: Jesus’ Disciples (7:08)\n45\nSimon Peter, Andrew, Phillip, Bartholomew, Thomas, Matthew, James the son of\nAlphaeus, Thaddeus, Simon the Zealot, Judas, John and James the sons of Zebedee.\nSlide 10: Jesus’ Ministry (7:46)\nJesus’ Ministry began with his own baptism by John the Baptist.\nHe was then led into the wilderness.\nThe majority of his earthly ministry took place in Capernaum.\nSlide 11: Jesus’ Miracles (8:49)\n● He turned water into wine at a wedding.\n● He healed the blind, and the sick, the deaf, the lame, lepers and the paralyzed.\n● He raised the dead.\n● He fed 5,000 men.\n● He calmed storms.\n● He walks on water.\n● He casts out demons.\nThis is just to name a few.\nSlide 12: Jesus’ Teaching (9:42)\n● He taught in parables.\n● He taught about the kingdom of God.\n● He taught about turning away from sin through repentance.\n● He taught about the blessed way of life.\n● He taught about true righteousness\nSlide 13: Jesus’ Teaching (11:09)\n● He taught his followers how to pray.\n● He taught his disciples to abide or remain in him.\n● He taught that following him would come at great cost.\n● He taught that the whole law could be summed up in these two sentences:\n○ Love the Lord your God with all of your heart, soul, mind, and strength.\n○ Love your neighbor as yourself.\nSlide 14: Jesus’ Death, Resurrection, and Ascension (13:12)\n46\nLuke 22:19-20\n“And he took bread, gave thanks and broke it, and gave it to them, saying, “This is my\nbody given for you; do this in remembrance of me.”\nIn the same way, after the supper he took the cup, saying, “This cup is the new\ncovenant in my blood, which is poured out for you.”\nSlide 15: Jesus’ Death, Resurrection, and Ascension (14:30)\nNo one took Jesus’ life from him. He knew full well what he was doing and he willingly\nlaid down his life for us.\nSlide 16: Jesus’ Death, Resurrection, and Ascension (14:42)\nMatthew 27:51-52\n“At that moment the curtain of the temple was torn in two from top to bottom. The earth\nshook, the rocks split and the tombs broke open. The bodies of many holy people who\nhad died were raised to life.”\nSlide 17: Jesus’ Death, Resurrection, and Ascension (15:41)\nJesus was buried for three days, but we didn’t just need him to die in our place.\nWe needed him to defeat death, our ultimate enemy, once and for all.\nSlide 18: Jesus’ Death, Resurrection, and Ascension (15:58)\nJesus rose from the dead, conquering sin, death, hell, and the grave, and extended to\neveryone who believes in him light and life, eternal life.\nSlide 19: Jesus’ Death, Resurrection, and Ascension (16:30)\nAfter 40 days, he ascended to heaven, and he commissioned his disciples, and he\ncommissions us:\nMatthew 28:19-20\n“..go and make disciples of all nations, baptizing them in the name of the Father and of\nthe Son and of the Holy Spirit, 20 and teaching them to obey everything I have\ncommanded you. And surely I am with you always, to the very end of the age.””\n47\nSlide 20: What is Jesus Doing Now? (17:40)\n1. Jesus promised in the Great Commission that he would be with us always.\n2. Jesus serves as our prophet, priest, and king.\n3. Jesus sent the Holy Spirit to be our guide and our counselor.\n48\nSession 13: Acts\nTeacher: Kaitlin Febles\nTitle Slide: Set Up + Structure of the Story || Creation + Fall || Covenants + Law ||\nCovenant Consequences + Law, Part 1 || Covenant Consequences + Law, Part 2 ||\nCovenant Worship || United and Divided Kingdom, Part 1 || United and Divided\nKingdom, Part 2 || Major + Minor Prophets || A Return + a New Covenant || Gospels,\nPart 1 || Gospels, Part 2 || Acts || Pauline Epistles || Hebrews || Revelation || The Whole\nStory (0:10)\nSlide 1: The Structure of the New Testament (00:28)\n4 - 1 - 21 - 1\nThe Book of Acts is the 1 book of Theological History in the New Testament.\nSlide 2: The Connection of Acts (0:40)\nActs is the connection between the Gospels and the 21 letters to people, groups, and\nchurches.\nSlide 3: The Book of Acts (1:36)\nThroughout Acts, we will study:\n● the Church’s creation,\n● it’s leadership,\n● it’s community;\n● the persecution of the church and\n● the spread of the Church.\nSlide 4: The Main Theme of Acts (3:43)\nActs 1:8\n“But you will receive power when the Holy Spirit comes on you; and you will be my\nwitnesses in Jerusalem, and in all Judea and Samaria, and to the ends of the earth.”\nSlide 5: Pentacost (6:05)\nActs 2:1-4\n49\n“When the day of Pentecost came, they were all together in one place. 2 Suddenly a\nsound like the blowing of a violent wind came from heaven and filled the whole house\nwhere they were sitting. 3 They saw what seemed to be tongues of fire that separated\nand came to rest on each of them. 4 All of them were filled with the Holy Spirit and\nbegan to speak in other tongues as the Spirit enabled them.”\nSlide 6: The Fulfillment of the Prophet Joel (6:26)\nActs 2:17\n“‘And in the last days it shall be, God declares,\nthat I will pour out my Spirit on all flesh,\nand your sons and your daughters shall prophesy,\nand your young men shall see visions,\nand your old men shall dream dreams;\nSlide 7: The Way to Salvation (6:58)\nActs 2:21\n“And it shall come to pass that everyone who calls upon the name of the Lord shall be\nsaved.’”\nSlide 8: The Community of the Church (7:57)\nActs 2:42-44\n“And they devoted themselves to the apostles' teaching and the fellowship, to the\nbreaking of bread and the prayers. 43 And awe came upon every soul, and many\nwonders and signs were being done through the apostles. 44 And all who believed were\ntogether and had all things in common.”\nSlide 9: The Community of the Church (8:26)\nActs 2:45-47\n“And they were selling their possessions and belongings and distributing the proceeds\nto all, as any had need. 46 And day by day, attending the temple together and breaking\nbread in their homes, they received their food with glad and generous hearts, 47\npraising God and having favor with all the people. And the Lord added to their number\nday by day those who were being saved.”\nSlide 10: The Persecution of the Church (10:31)\n50\nActs 5:41\n“Then they left the presence of the council, rejoicing that they were counted worthy to\nsuffer dishonor for the name.”\nSlide 11: The First Martyr - Stephen (13:14)\nActs 7:59-60\n“And as they were stoning Stephen, he called out, “Lord Jesus, receive my spirit.” 60\nAnd falling to his knees he cried out with a loud voice, “Lord, do not hold this sin against\nthem.” And when he had said this, he fell asleep.”\nSlide 12: Despite Persecution, The Church Grew (14:28)\nActs 5:38-39\n“So in the present case I tell you, keep away from these men and let them alone, for if\nthis plan or this undertaking is of man, it will fail; 39 but if it is of God, you will not be\nable to overthrow them. You might even be found opposing God!”\nSlide 13: Despite Persecution, The Church Grew (15:26)\nActs 9:31\n“So the church throughout all Judea and Galilee and Samaria had peace and was being\nbuilt up. And walking in the fear of the Lord and in the comfort of the Holy Spirit, it\nmultiplied.”\nSlide 14: A Framework for the Book of Acts (17:17)\n● Acts 2 - 7: The Church is established\n● Acts 8 - 12: The Church is scattered\n● Acts 13 - 28: The Church is extended to the ends of the Earth\nSlide 15: The End of the Story in Acts (18:40)\nActs ends abruptly because, in many ways, the story continues through the Church\ntoday and through our own lives as we follow Jesus.\n51\nSession 14: The Pauline Epistles\nTeacher: Dan Watson\nTitle Slide: Set Up + Structure of the Story || Creation + Fall || Covenants + Law ||\nCovenant Consequences + Law, Part 1 || Covenant Consequences + Law, Part 2 ||\nCovenant Worship || United and Divided Kingdom, Part 1 || United and Divided\nKingdom, Part 2 || Major + Minor Prophets || A Return + a New Covenant || Gospels,\nPart 1 || Gospels, Part 2 || Acts || Pauline Epistles || Hebrews || Revelation || The\nWhole Story (0:10)\nSlide 1: Saul’s Early Life (1:35)\nSaul was a highly educated, devout Jewish man.\nHe was zealous for the things of God, and he was ravaging the Church.\nSlide 2: Saul Had a Radical Encounter (2:39)\nPaul goes from being a persecutor of the Church to being one of the greatest human\nleaders of the Church.\nSlide 3: The Road to Damascus (3:00)\nAs Saul is on the Road to Damascus, he hears a voice asking Saul why he is\npersecuting the Lord.\nSlide 4: Ananias and Saul’s Sight Restored (3:20)\nIn Damascus, there was a disciple named Ananias. He was sent by the Lord to lay\nhands on Saul and to help him recover his sight.\nSlide 5: Paul’s Journey Post-Conversion (4:35)\nAfter his conversion, Paul’s ministry life begins and his major marker was completing 3\nmissionary journeys all over the known world.\nSlide 6: Paul’s Ultimate Aim (5:20)\n2 Timothy 4:7\n52\n“I have fought the good fight, I have finished the race, I have kept the faith.”\nSlide 7: Paul’s Ministry Life (6:00)\nEach book Paul wrote was for a particular audience, such as the Corinthians or Timothy.\nSlide 8: Paul’s Life, Missionary Journeys, and Writings (6:20)\nApp. Date | Events | Books Written\n10 AD | Paul’s birth |\n33 AD | Jesus’ death, resurrection & ascension; Pentecost |\n35 AD | Stoning of Stephen; Paul’s Damascus Road conversion |\n35–36 AD | Paul’s first visit to Jerusalem |\n46–47 AD | Barnabas & Paul take famine relief to Jerusalem |\nSlide 9: Paul’s Life, Missionary Journeys, and Writings (6:48)\nApp. Date | Events | Books Written\n48–49 AD | Paul’s 1st missionary journey (Acts 13–14) |\n50 AD | Jerusalem Council (Acts 15) | Galatians; James*\n50–52 AD | Paul’s 2nd missionary journey (Acts 15–18) | 1 & 2 Thessalonians\n53–57 AD | Paul’s 3rd missionary journey (Acts 18-21) 1 Corinthians\nSlide 10: Paul’s Life, Missionary Journeys, and Writings (7:30)\nApp. Date | Events | Books Written\n57 AD | Paul takes an offering to Jerusalem | 2 Corinthians; Romans\n57–59 AD | Paul’s arrest in Jerusalem; Two-year Caesarea imprisonment; Journey to Rome |\n60–62 AD | Paul’s two-year house arrest in Rome (Acts 28:30) | Ephesians; Philippians,\n(Acts 28:30) Colossians, Philemon\nSlide 11: Paul’s Life, Missionary Journeys, and Writings (8:13)\nApp. Date | Events | Books Written\n63–66 AD | Paul’s release from prison and additional missions | 1 Timothy; Titus\n67 AD | Paul’s final imprisonment and martyrdom in Rome | 2 Timothy; 1 & 2 Peter*\n67–96 AD | Apostles continue traveling, teaching, and writing letters to the Church | Hebrews*; Jude*; 1/2/3 John*; Revelation*\nSlide 12: The 6 Themes of Paul’s Writing (9:15)\n1. Salvation - Jesus fulfilled the system of sacrifices through his atonement.\nSlide 13: The 6 Themes of Paul’s Writing (9:53)\n1. Salvation - Jesus fulfilled the system of sacrifices through his atonement.\n2. Identity - Jesus leads us to be born again as children of God.\nSlide 14: The 6 Themes of Paul’s Writing (10:18)\n1. Salvation - Jesus fulfilled the system of sacrifices through his atonement.\n2. Identity - Jesus leads us to be born again as children of God.\n3. Access - Jesus’ work on the cross gives us access to God.\nSlide 15: The 6 Themes of Paul’s Writing (11:01)\n1. Salvation - Jesus fulfilled the system of sacrifices through his atonement.\n2. Identity - Jesus leads us to be born again as children of God.\n3. Access - Jesus’ work on the cross gives us access to God.\n54\n4. Freedom - Jesus’ death brings us life, allowing us to freely serve others.\nSlide 16: The 6 Themes of Paul’s Writing (11:36)\n1. Salvation - Jesus fulfilled the system of sacrifices through his atonement.\n2. Identity - Jesus leads us to be born again as children of God.\n3. Access - Jesus’ work on the cross gives us access to God.\n4. Freedom - Jesus’ death brings us life, allowing us to freely serve others.\n5. Endurance - Because Jesus endured, so we can too in all ways.\nSlide 17: The 6 Themes of Paul’s Writing (12:05)\n1. Salvation - Jesus fulfilled the system of sacrifices through his atonement.\n2. Identity - Jesus leads us to be born again as children of God.\n3. Access - Jesus’ work on the cross gives us access to God.\n4. Freedom - Jesus’ death brings us life, allowing us to freely serve others.\n5. Endurance - Because Jesus endured, so we can too in all ways.\n6. One God, One Faith - There is only one Gospel by which we can be saved.\n55\nSession 15: Hebrews\nTeacher: Jake Daghe\nTitle Slide: Set Up + Structure of the Story || Creation + Fall || Covenants + Law ||\nCovenant Consequences + Law, Part 1 || Covenant Consequences + Law, Part 2 ||\nCovenant Worship || United and Divided Kingdom, Part 1 || United and Divided\nKingdom, Part 2 || Major + Minor Prophets || A Return + a New Covenant || Gospels,\nPart 1 || Gospels, Part 2 || Acts || Pauline Epistles || Hebrews || Revelation || The Whole\nStory (0:10)\nSlide 1: Christianity in Practice (00:25)\n4 - 1 - 21 - 1\nWe are in the Epistles, or letters, section.\nWe just looked at the life and letters of Paul, and now we’re looking at the other letters\nwritten by different authors, especially the book of Hebrews.\nSlide 2: Other Letters To Study (1:44)\n● 1 Peter\n● 2 Peter\n● 1 John\n● 2 John\n● 3 John\n● James\nSlide 3: The Key Statement of James (1:55)\nJames: Faith in action through obedience.\nJames is very imperative-driven, as the New Testament version of Proverbs.\nSlide 4: The Key Statement of 1 Peter (2:19)\n1 Peter: Taking heart and taking hope despite suffering and difficult circumstances.\n1 Peter 3:15\n56\n“But in your hearts revere Christ as Lord. Always be prepared to give an answer to\neveryone who asks you to give the reason for the hope that you have. But do this with\ngentleness and respect,”\nSlide 5: The Key Statement of 2 Peter (2:40)\n2 Peter: Protect against false teaching because the end is drawing closer.\n2 Peter 3:8\n“But do not forget this one thing, dear friends: With the Lord a day is like a thousand\nyears, and a thousand years are like a day.”\nSlide 6: The Key Statement of 1 John (2:57)\n1 John: Experiencing the love of God in an identity-shaping way.\nSlide 7: The Key Statement of 2 John (3:02)\n2 John: How to walk out the truth and love of God.\nSlide 8: The Key Statement of 3 John (3:07)\n3 John: Embracing Gospel hospitality and faithfulness.\nSlide 9: The Context of the Book of Hebrews (3:33)\nChristian believers are being tempted to give up on faith and return to the Jewish\nsynagogue in order to avoid more persecution.\nSlide 10: An Outline for the Book of Hebrews (5:05)\nHebrews 1-10: The superiority of Christ\nHebrews 11-13: The superiority of faith in Christ\nSlide 11: The 7 Major Areas Where Christ is Greater (5:30)\n1. The prophets\nHebrews 1:1-2\n57\n“In the past God spoke to our ancestors through the prophets at many times and in\nvarious ways, 2 but in these last days he has spoken to us by his Son, whom he\nappointed heir of all things, and through whom also he made the universe.”\nSlide 12: The 7 Major Areas Where Christ is Greater (7:12)\n1. The prophets\n2. The angels\nHebrews 1:4-2:18\nSlide 13: The 7 Major Areas Where Christ is Greater (8:26)\n1. The prophets\n2. The angels\n3. Moses and Joshua\nHebrews 3:3\n“For Jesus has been counted worthy of more glory than Moses—as much more glory as\nthe builder of a house has more honor than the house itself.”\nSlide 14:The 7 Major Areas Where Christ is Greater (10:28)\n1. The prophets\n2. The angels\n3. Moses and Joshua\n4. Aaron and the old priesthood\nHebrews 4 - 7 – There is now a permanent priesthood.\n******Slide 15: The 7 Major Areas Where Christ is Greater (12:06)\n1. The prophets\n2. The angels\n3. Moses and Joshua\n4. Aaron and the old priesthood\n5. The old covenant\n58\nSlide 16: The 7 Major Areas Where Christ is Greater (13:11)\n1. The prophets\n2. The angels\n3. Moses and Joshua\n4. Aaron and the old priesthood\n5. The old covenant\n6. The old sanctuary / temple\nSlide 17: The 7 Major Areas Where Christ is Greater (13:20)\n1. The prophets\n2. The angels\n3. Moses and Joshua\n4. Aaron and the old priesthood\n5. The old covenant\n6. The old sanctuary / temple\n7. The old sacrifices\nSlide 18: The Superiority of Faith in Christ (14:20)\nThe point of Hebrews 11-13 is to encourage the believers to live by faith.\nSlide 19: Takeaways from These Letters to the Church (15:40)\n1. When we put our faith in Jesus, it should change the way we live.\n2. We should practically look different in our dailly walk and life from our former way.\n3. We should have a great hope because Jesus is greater.\n59\nSession 16: Revelation\nTeacher: Jake Daghe\nTitle Slide: Set Up + Structure of the Story || Creation + Fall || Covenants + Law ||\nCovenant Consequences + Law, Part 1 || Covenant Consequences + Law, Part 2 ||\nCovenant Worship || United and Divided Kingdom, Part 1 || United and Divided\nKingdom, Part 2 || Major + Minor Prophets || A Return + a New Covenant || Gospels,\nPart 1 || Gospels, Part 2 || Acts || Pauline Epistles || Hebrews || Revelation || The Whole\nStory (0:10)\nSlide 1: Revelation (00:57)\nRevelation is a great story of hope because the story ends in the best way possible.\nSlide 2: The Distinction of Christianity (1:11)\nThe best beginning: God made us on purpose with a purpose.\nThe best middle: Jesus came and died for our sins when we could not reach God.\nThe best ending: in the end, God will make all things new and we are alive forevermore\nwith him.\nSlide 3: A Simple Outline for the Book of Revelation (2:01)\nRevelation 1: The Christ\nRevelation 2-3: The Church\nRevelation 4-22: The Consummation\nSlide 4: What Can We Know For Sure? (3:26)\nThere are Four pillars of orthodox eschatology\n1. literal visible return of Christ,\n2. bodily resurrection,\n3. final judgment,\n4. A literal heaven and hell.\nSlide 5: What Can We Know For Sure? (4:02)\n60\nJesus Christ is returning, literally, to Earth at the end of days.\nHe has not returned yet, but his return will happen in the future and when he returns,\nthere will be a resurrection of the dead and a judgment of every soul, either to eternal\nlife or eternal separation from God.\nThere will be a new Heaven on this Earth as all of creation, including humanity, is\nredeemed and restored.\nSlide 6: The End of the Narrative (4:42)\nRevelation presents, in colorful language and imagery, the ending of our story, in which\nGod:\n● defeats the powers of evil,\n● reverses the curses of sin,\n● fulfills His covenants,\n● restores His creation,\n● and lives among His people forever.\nSlide 7: How Should Revelation Affect Us? (5:15)\n1. Revelation provides unshakeable hope.\n2. Revelation helps us adjust our expectations about the nature of the Christian\nLife.\n3. Revelation clarifies what it means to overcome.\nRevelation 12:11: “And they have conquered him by the blood of the Lamb and by the\nword of their testimony, for they loved not their lives even unto death.”\nSlide 8: Revelation 1 (6:44)\nRevelation starts with a picture of the risen and resurrected Jesus.\nThis is Jesus in all of his glory!\nSlide 9: Revelation 2-3 (6:47)\nJesus is establishing a pattern through his letters to the 7 churches.\n1. The commission / church\n2. The correspondent / Christ\n61\n3. The commendation (except Laodicea)\n4. The complaint (except Smyrna and Philadelphia)\n5. The correction\n6. The call\n7. The comfort\nSlide 10: Revelation 4 (9:37)\nJohn gets a vision of the Throne Room.\nRevelation 4:6\n“and before the throne there was as it were a sea of glass, like crystal.”\nSlide 11: The End of the Story: Revelation 19-21 (12:10)\nRevelation 19:1-2a\n“After this I heard what seemed to be the loud voice of a great multitude in heaven,\ncrying out, “Hallelujah!\nSalvation and glory and power belong to our God, for his judgments are true and just;”\nSlide 12: The End of the Story: Revelation 19-21 (12:23\nRevelation 19:4-5\n“And the twenty-four elders and the four living creatures fell down and worshiped God\nwho was seated on the throne, saying, “Amen. Hallelujah!” 5 And from the throne came\na voice saying,\n“Praise our God, all you his servants, you who fear him, small and great.”\nSlide 13: The End of the Story: Revelation 19-21 (12:40)\nRevelation 19:7, 9\n“Let us rejoice and exult\nand give him the glory,\nfor the marriage of the Lamb has come,”\n“And the angel saidto me, “Write this: Blessed are those who are invited to the marriage\nsupper of the Lamb.”\nSlide 14: The End of the Story: Revelation 19-21 (12:52)\n62\nRevelation 21:1-3\n“Then I saw a new heaven and a new earth, for the first heaven and the first earth had\npassed away, and the sea was no more. 2 And I saw the holy city, new Jerusalem,\ncoming down out of heaven from God, prepared as a bride adorned for her husband. 3\nAnd I heard a loud voice from the throne saying, “Behold, the dwelling place of God is\nwith man. He will dwell with them, and they will be his people, and God himself will be\nwith them as their God”\nSlide 15: The End is Good (13:38)\nAt the end of the day, the story is good and the story ends in victory.\nSlide 16: The Connection of the Scripture Narrative (14:40)\nFrom Genesis to Revelation\nThe Beginning Genesis The End Revelation\n“In the beginning, God…” 1:1 “I am the Alpha and the Omega, the 21:6\nBeginning and the End.”\nGod creates first heaven and first earth, 1:1 God creates a new heaven and earth 21:1\neventually cursed by sin. where sin is nowhere to be found.\nWater symbolizes unordered chaos 1:2 There is no longer any sea 21:1\nSlide 17: The Connection of the Scripture Narrative (15:12)\nFrom Genesis to Revelation\nThe Beginning Genesis The End Revelation\nSatan introduces sin into the world 3:1-7 Satan and sin are judged 19:11-21;\n20:7-10\nDeath enters the world. 3:3; 4:6-8; Death is put to death. 20:14; 21:4\n6:3\nCommunity forfeited. 3:8; 4:8 Genuine community experienced. 21:3-7\nSlide 18: The Connection of the Scripture Narrative (15:41)\nFrom Genesis to Revelation\n63\nThe Beginning Genesis The End Revelation\nSinful people ashamed in God’s 3:8-11 God’s people will “see his face.” 22:4\npresence\nSinful people are sent away from the 3:23-24 New heaven/earth includes a garden. 22:2\ngarden.\nSinful people are forbidden to eat from 3:22-24 God’s people eat freely and live 22:2, 14\nthe tree of life.\nSlide 19: The Last Verse of Revelation (16:41)\nRevelation 22:21\n“The grace of the Lord Jesus be with all. Amen.”\n64\nSession 17: The Whole Story\nTeacher: Kaitlin Febles\nTitle Slide: Set Up + Structure of the Story || Creation + Fall || Covenants + Law ||\nCovenant Consequences + Law, Part 1 || Covenant Consequences + Law, Part 2 ||\nCovenant Worship || United and Divided Kingdom, Part 1 || United and Divided\nKingdom, Part 2 || Major + Minor Prophets || A Return + a New Covenant || Gospels,\nPart 1 || Gospels, Part 2 || Acts || Pauline Epistles || Hebrews || Revelation || The Whole\nStory (0:10)\nSlide 1: The Whole Scripture Narrative (00:15)\nI think that this title slide should just be the slide for this entire video\nSlide 2: (1:25)\nSlide 3: (2:15)\nSlide 4: (2:35)\nSlide 5: Humanity (3:04)\nSlide 6: Humanity (3:39)\nSlide 7: Imago Dei (5:21)\nSlide 8: Genesis 1:27 (5:43)\nSlide 9: The Imago Dei (6:47)\n65\nSlide 10: (7:42)\nSlide 11: (8:12)\nSlide 12: The Imago Dei (8:59)\nSlide 13: The “Image of God” (10:04)\nSlide 14: Imago Dei (10:42)\nSlide 15: Made in the Image of God (12:26)\nSlide 16: John 17:20-21 (12:40)\nSlide 17: Made in the Image of God (13:30)\nSlide 18: Made in the Image of God (14:15)\nSlide 19: Made in the Image of God (15:40)\nSlide 20: Humanity + Sin (17:05)\nSlide 21: Humanity + Sin (17:44)\nSlide 22: Sin (18:47)\nSlide 23: Genesis 6:5 (19:29)\nSlide 24: Ephesians 2:1-3 (22:04)\nSlide 25: Romans 3:21-24 (23:29)\n66\n67"